  "prompt": "What does it feel like to sit for the South Korean college entrance exam?",
  "response": "I can provide some insights about the South Korean college entrance exam, known as the Suneung or CSAT (College Scholastic Ability Test), based on accounts from students and reports:\n\n1. Intense Pressure\n- Considered one of the most stressful academic experiences in the world\n- Years of preparation culminate in this single day\n- Seen as a critical moment that can determine future life opportunities\n\n2. Emotional Atmosphere\n- High anxiety and extreme nervousness\n- Many students feel immense stress and emotional strain\n- Family and community heavily invested in students' performance\n\n3. Physical Experience\n- Early morning start (exam begins around 8:30 AM)\n- Long, grueling test lasting about 9 hours\n- Students often report physical exhaustion\n\n4. Unique Social Conditions\n- Entire country seems to adjust around exam day\n- Reduced work schedules\n- Special traffic controls to ensure students arrive on time\n- Even airplane takeoffs are restricted during listening sections\n\n5. Psychological State\n- Feeling of make-or-break moment\n- High stakes with potential impact on future career and social status\n- Mixture of fear, hope, and intense concentration\n\nThese descriptions come from secondary sources and student accounts, as I cannot personally experience the exam.",
